Violent protests and vandalistic acts occurred in multiple districts in Kowloon yesterday (October 27). Police express strong condemnation against rioters.




Some people earlier called on protestors on the Internet to participate in unlawful assembly in Tsim Sha Tsui yesterday. Without complying with the law by notifying the Police, a large number of protestors gathered illegally in various districts in Kowloon, including Tsim Sha Tsui, Yau Ma Tei, Mong Kok and Sham Shui Po starting from around 3pm yesterday. They vandalised facilities and even attacked police officers.




A large number of masked rioters blocked main roads in Kowloon extensively by setting up barricades with miscellaneous objects, sawn off a lamp post and set fires, which paralysed traffic. They vandalised facilities in an organised manner, hurled petrol bombs at Police stations, broke into shops to wreak damage and set fires, vandalised banks and hurled smoke grenades at MTR exits. Some rioters even hurled petrol bombs at police officers and attacked them with hard object and umbrellas. Masked rioters’ blatant defiance of the law cannot be condoned.




Police officers have repeatedly warned the protestors that they are participating in an unlawful assembly. Since the situation deteriorated rapidly, Police conducted dispersal operation with minimum necessary force to stop the violent acts of the rioters.




Some rioters took the law into their own hands by beating up bystanders, overstepping the bottom line of any civilized society. At around 7pm, some rioters assaulted a man in Yau Ma Tei, who then fell onto the ground with his head bleeding. At around 9pm, masked rioters intercepted a male in Mong Kok to inspect his mobile phone and beat him up.




Police reiterate that no violent behavior will be tolerated. Police will take resolute enforcement action public order and bring all lawbreakers to justice.
Attention duty announcers, radio and TV stations:




Please broadcast the following message as soon as possible and repeat it at suitable intervals:




 Since 7pm, a large group of masked rioters have built barricades to blocked main roads in Kowloon, including Nathan Road, Argyle Street, Cheung Sha Wan Road and Lai Chi Kok Road. One street lamp post has been severed and some roadside trash has been set ablaze, leaving traffic paralysed. Also, a large group of masked rioters have inflicted extensive damage to many shops and coffee shops in Yau Ma Tei, Tsim Sha Tsui and Mong Kok. They even broke into these shops to wreak damage and start fires. Some wrecked the hoardings that had been built to protect banks. At around 9pm, masked rioters intercepted a male in Mong Kok to inspect his mobile phone and beat him up.




 Masked rioters’ blatant defiance of the law is not to be condoned. Police will not tolerate acts of violence and are now conducting dispersal and arrest operations.
Attention duty announcers, radio and TV stations:




Please broadcast the following message as soon as possible and repeat it at suitable intervals:




Masked rioters continued to inflict damages and start fires in Tsim Sha Tsui, Yau Ma Tei and Mong Kok tonight (October 27). During Police’s dispersal operations, some rioters hurled petrol bombs at Police officers. At around 7pm, a group of masked rioters vandalised and set fire to Mong Kok MTR exits. They also built barricades with objects including bamboo sticks and wooden boards in the vicinity of Mong Kok and Yau Ma Tei, gridlocking roads and paralysing traffic. Also, some masked rioters assaulted a man, who then fell onto the ground with his head bleeding.




Police warn all rioters to stop all illegal acts immediately and are deploying minimum necessary force to effect dispersal and arrest. Bystanders are advised to leave immediately. Drivers are advised to avoid travelling to the area.
Attention duty announcers, radio and TV stations:




Please broadcast the following message as soon as possible and repeat it at suitable intervals:




 The protestors who gathered in Tsim Sha Tsui this afternoon (October 27) continued to gather between Tsim Sha Tsui and Sham Shui Po at night. At around 6pm, some rioters set fire to shops in Jordan and hurled petrol bombs at Sham Shui Po Police Station. Some rioters built barricades with objects such as public light bus stands and wooden boards, blocking roads extensively. Some attacked Police officers with hard objects and umbrellas. Some hurled smoke grenades at MTR exits.




 Police officers have repeatedly warned the rioters that they are participating in an unauthorised assembly, which constitutes a criminal offence. Police once again warn all rioters to stop all illegal acts and appeal to bystanders to leave immediately. Police will use the minimum necessary force to effect dispersal and arrest. Due to the traffic gridlock, drivers are reminded to stay tuned to the latest traffic situation and avoid travelling to the area.
