Attention duty announcers, radio and TV stations:Please broadcast the following message as soon as possible and repeat it at suitable intervals:At around 3pm, rioters threw petrol bombs inside Kowloon Tong MTR Station, posing a threat to the safety of citizens.  No one was injured.  Facilities in Kowloon Tong MTR Station were seriously damaged.  Police officers have been deployed to handle the incident.  G1 and G2 exits of Kowloon Tong MTR Station are now closed.Police warn the rioters to stop all illegal acts immediately. We express condemnation against all violent acts and will investigate into the case thoroughly.Members of the public are reminded to stay tuned to the latest situation. In case of danger, they should leave the scene immediately and report to the Police.
Police today (October 12) laid a holding charge against a 51-year-old woman with one count of murder.The woman was arrested on October 10 in suspected connection with a murder and attempted suicide case in Tin Shui Wai on the same day, in which her 16-year-old daughter died.The case will be mentioned at Tuen Mun Magistrates' Courts on October 14.
Police advise motorists that special traffic arrangements will be implemented in Sha Tin to facilitate the race meeting today (October 12).




 The arrangements will come into effect two hours before the start of the first race and will last until the crowds have dispersed after the race meeting.




 Appropriate traffic signs will be put up and police will be on hand to guide motorists.




 The Police also appeal to people going to Sha Tin Racecourse for the race meeting and to Happy Valley Racecourse for cross betting to make maximum use of public transport.




 Parking spaces at the two racecourses are available only to holders of appropriate permits issued by Hong Kong Jockey Club and any vehicles illegally parked will be towed away.


Police are investigating a fatal traffic accident in Wan Chai today (October 12) in which a 33-year-old man died.




At about 1.05am, a private car driven by a 28-year-old man was travelling along Gloucester Road towards Central. When approaching near Luard Road, it reportedly rolled over the 33-year-old man who was lying on the road.




Sustaining serious head injuries, the man was certified dead at scene.




The private car driver was arrested for dangerous driving causing death. He is being detained for further enquiries.




Investigation by the Special Investigation Team of Traffic, Hong Kong Island is underway.




 Anyone who witnessed the accident or has any information to offer is urged to contact the investigating officers on 3660 6849 or 3660 6848.


A man who went missing in Wong Tai Sin has been located.




 Tang Ming-chuen, aged 75, went missing after he left his residence on Tai Shing Street on October 7 afternoon. His family made a report to Police on October 9.




 The man turned up to Police to cancel the missing person report tonight (October 11). He sustained no injuries and no suspicious circumstances were detected.
Since early October, Police received four reports from different merchants that they received messages by fax or email since late September, coercing them to fund violent protests by Bitcoin. The merchants were threatened to comply or their shops would be wrecked.




 Police accord high priority to such cases and are carrying out active investigations. Any members of the public or merchants who have any information to offer; or have received relevant blackmailing or intimidating messages, please contact Police on 5975 3133 or email to appeal@police.gov.hk.


