A large group of masked rioters repeatedly committed destructive acts extensively and blocking roads in various districts in Hong Kong yesterday (October 7). Police express severe condemnation against rioters.




Starting from around 8pm, a large group of masked rioters participated in unlawful assemblies at multiple locations, including Mong Kok, Wong Tai Sin, Tai Po, Sha Tin, Tuen Mun, Tsuen Wan, Yuen Long, Tai Koo and Tseung Kwan O. Rioters set up barricades, set fire to miscellaneous objects and dug up bricks from the pavements to block major roads.




Besides, rioters continued to commit destructive acts extensively in various districts. They vandalised shopping malls, shops, MTR station facilities including turnstile and ticket machines and also damaged traffic lights. Their acts were completely lawless.




Since the situation deteriorated rapidly, Police conducted dispersal operation with appropriate force, including tear gases, rubber bullets, bean bag rounds and 40mm react round to stop the violent acts of the protestors.




At around 9pm, during Police’s dispersal operation in Tseung Kwan O, some rioters suddenly dropped a bicycle from height, hitting an officer’s head. The officer fell onto the ground and was escorted to the hospital by his colleagues. He sustained injuries to his head and neck. Police strongly condemn the life-threatening and violent acts of rioters.




Police strongly condemns the rioters' violent and vandalistic acts which completely disregard law and order. Police reiterate that no violent behavior will be tolerated. Police will continue to take resolute enforcement action so as to safeguard the city’s public safety and bring all lawbreakers to justice.
Attention duty announcers, radio and TV stations:Please broadcast the following message as soon as possible and repeat it at suitable intervals:Some masked rioters are currently gathering in Yuen Long and Tseung Kwan O, setting fire to miscellaneous objects on the road. Explosions were heard. In Mong Kok, some are still illegally occupying roads and paralysing traffic. Since around 9pm, the Police officers have given repeated warnings to disperse the protestors but they still refused to leave. Police warn all protestors to leave immediately and stop all illegal acts. Officers will conduct arrest operations.
Attention duty announcers, radio and TV stations:




Please broadcast the following message as soon as possible and repeat it at suitable intervals:




As the night fell, a large group of masked rioters have committed various violent acts including damaging public properties and facilities in various MTR stations, and arson in districts including Yuen Long, Sha Tin, Tai Po, Wong Tai Sin, Tseung Kwan O and Tai Koo. Such acts jeopardise public safety. In Yuen Long, some masked rioters smashed up facilities with long metal rods and hard objects and set fire in Tai Tong Road Light Rail Station. In Mong Kok and Tseung Kwan O, a large group of masked rioters have occupied roads. Despite the use of tear gas by police officers, rioters still refused to leave.




Police warn all offenders to stop all violent acts and leave the scene immediately. Members of the public in the vicinity are advised to stay in safe places.
Attention duty announcers, radio and TV stations:




Please broadcast the following message as soon as possible and repeat it at suitable intervals:




Since around 8pm, a large group of masked rioters have been committing destructive acts extensively and blocking roads in various districts. In Sha Tin, some masked rioters smashed glass in shopping centres, broke through a roll-up gate before storming the Sha Tin Wai MTR Station to wreck facilities including turnstile and ticket machines, and damaged traffic lights. In Tsuen Wan, some masked rioters broke roll-up gates of MTR stations; whereas in Tuen Mun and Tai Koo, they occupied roads illegally.




Police warn all rioters to stop all illegal acts and will enforce the law resolutely, bringing offenders to justice.
Attention duty announcers, radio and TV stations:




Please broadcast the following message as soon as possible and repeat it at suitable intervals:




 A large group of masked protestors have gathered outside Mong Kok Police station this evening (October 7). Some have dug up bricks from pavements and set barricades with miscellaneous objects including large rubbish bins, railings and public light bus stop poles at the junction of Nathan Road and Prince Edward Road West, paralysing traffic.




 Police warn all protestors to stop all illegal acts immediately and will soon conduct dispersal and arrest operations.
Owing to the thunderstorm warning, the flag-raising ceremony to be conducted at Golden Bauhinia Square, Wan Chai at 8am today (October 7) will be cancelled.


Massive violent protests again broke out in multiple districts in Hong Kong yesterday (October 6). Police express severe condemnation against rioters.




 Some people earlier called on protestors on the Internet to participate in unlawful assemblies at multiple locations on Hong Kong Island and in Kowloon yesterday. Without complying with the law by notifying the Police, a large number of protestors gathered illegally in various locations including Causeway Bay, Central, Admiralty, Tsim Sha Tsui, Mong Kok, Kowloon Tong and Sham Shui Po starting from around 2pm yesterday.




 Rioters continued to set fire, block roads and vandalise facilities extensively in various districts. They set up barricades, set fire to miscellaneous objects and dug up bricks from the pavements to block major roads. In Wan Chai, protestor suspectedly drove away a drilling vehicle from a construction site without authority and attempted to drill carriageways. Rioters also endangered public safety, hurling petrol bombs at police officers and a reporter was hit by petrol bomb. Moreover, rioters vandalised banks, MTR station facilities and shops. Their acts were completely lawless.




 Since the situation deteriorated rapidly, Police conducted dispersal operation with appropriate force, including tear gases, rubber bullets and bean bag rounds. The specialised crowd management vehicles were also deployed to stop the violent acts of the protestors.




 Some rioters took the law into their own hands by beating up bystanders, overstepping the bottom line of any civilized society. At around 5pm, a taxi driver was pulled out from his vehicle after a traffic accident at the junction of Cheung Sha Wan Road and Yen Chow Street in Sham Shui Po. Severely battered by some rioters, the taxi driver lied on the ground unconsciously and was covered in blood. Later on, a large group of rioters attacked a man and left him unconscious near Nathan Road in Mong Kok. A woman was also beaten up by some rioters in Mong Kok and suffered head injuries suspectedly due to taking photos of rioters’ acts of vandalism.




 Since June, radical protestors have been repeatedly organising unlawful activities. Their violent acts are spreading and escalating drastically, including the use of fatal violence to attack Police officers. Public safety has been jeopardised and the public order of the whole city is being pushed to the verge of a very dangerous situation. Police reiterate that no violent behavior will be tolerated. Police will continue to take resolute enforcement action so as to safeguard the city’s public safety and bring all lawbreakers to justice. Police appeal to the public to report illegal acts and join hands to maintain public order.
